  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>Google algorithm update</strong> is a change to the ranking systems — the models and heuristics that decide which pages surface for a query. Updates range from broad (Core Updates that touch every query) to narrow (Spam, Product Reviews, Helpful Content). Google shipped <strong>4,725 ranking changes in 2022</strong> alone; only a handful are announced.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Continuous · 4–6 named per year</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Technical SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Rollout window</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1–3 weeks (Core)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every SEO plan lives or dies on how it handles algorithm updates. Some updates barely move a domain. Others rewrite the entire top-10 for a query set overnight. Knowing which kind is landing — and reacting appropriately — is the difference between growth and quarters-long drops.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is an algorithm update?</h2>
        <p>Google's algorithm is not one thing. It is a stack of hundreds of ranking systems — RankBrain, BERT, MUM, HCU, SpamBrain, Passage Ranking, Freshness — each contributing signals to a final score. An update is a change to one or more of those systems.</p>
        <p>Updates come in three broad shapes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Core Updates</strong> — broad refreshes of overall quality scoring, rolled out over 1 to 3 weeks a few times per year</li>
          <li><strong>Named targeted updates</strong> — Spam, Product Reviews, Helpful Content, Link Spam</li>
          <li><strong>Unnamed everyday updates</strong> — thousands per year, most of them invisible</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The 4,725 number</div>
          <p>In its 2022 "How Search Works" report, Google disclosed <strong>4,725 launches</strong> after 800,000+ quality tests and 148,000 side-by-side experiments. Most sites feel almost none of them. The dozen or so announced updates are the ones that shift traffic at scale.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why algorithm updates matter</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Every ranking is temporary.</strong> A #1 spot today may not survive the next Core Update.</li>
          <li><strong>Updates redistribute traffic across a category.</strong> One site's loss is another site's gain — so someone always benefits.</li>
          <li><strong>They enforce quality standards.</strong> HCU and Spam Updates reset what "good enough" content looks like.</li>
          <li><strong>They fix Google's own gaps.</strong> AI-generated slop, thin affiliate pages, review-farm sites — Google uses updates to close loopholes.</li>
          <li><strong>Recovery windows are locked to update cycles.</strong> If your site drops in a Core Update, the earliest recovery is the next Core Update.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How algorithm updates work</h2>
        <p>Every named Google update runs on its own rollout timeline.</p>

        <h3>Announcement</h3>
        <p>Google's Search Liaison (Danny Sullivan) posts to X and the Search Central Blog when a rollout starts. This is the timestamp SEO tools use to correlate traffic changes with updates.</p>

        <h3>Rollout</h3>
        <p>Data centres pick up the new signals in stages. Ranking fluctuations are heaviest in the first week. Google announces "rollout complete" when 100% of infrastructure is on the new signal.</p>

        <h3>Re-evaluation</h3>
        <p>The updated system re-scores sites continuously. Sites that were dropped in the update cannot be re-evaluated until either (a) the same system runs again, or (b) a later update supersedes the signal.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Named Google algorithm updates</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Update</th><th>What it targets</th><th>Frequency</th><th>Rollout</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Core Update</strong></td>
                <td>Broad quality and relevance</td>
                <td>3–4 per year</td>
                <td>1–3 weeks</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Helpful Content Update</strong></td><td>Site-wide content usefulness</td><td>Now folded into Core</td><td>Continuous</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Spam Update</strong></td><td>Cloaking, scraping, doorway pages</td><td>2–3 per year</td><td>1–2 weeks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Link Spam Update</strong></td><td>Unnatural link patterns</td><td>1–2 per year</td><td>~2 weeks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product Reviews Update</strong></td><td>Thin affiliate reviews</td><td>Now folded into Core</td><td>Continuous</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reviews Update (expanded)</strong></td><td>Reviews of any kind</td><td>2 per year historically</td><td>2–4 weeks</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Recent notable algorithm updates</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>September 2023 Helpful Content Update.</strong> Devastated independent publishers, especially those using heavy AI content or thin affiliate content. Many sites lost 60–90% of traffic overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>March 2024 Core Update.</strong> Google claimed a 45% reduction in low-quality content in search results. AI content farms took heavy hits.</li>
          <li><strong>November 2023 Reviews Update.</strong> Expanded from just product reviews to reviews of services, businesses, and media. Set the depth-of-experience bar much higher.</li>
          <li><strong>2024 August Core Update.</strong> Started partial recoveries for HCU-impacted sites that had improved their content, though many stayed suppressed.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Core Update vs targeted update — which are you dealing with</h2>
        <p>Both cause traffic shifts. The response playbook is different.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Core Update signals</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Broad ranking shifts across many queries</li>
              <li>Overall E-E-A-T and relevance re-scored</li>
              <li>Fix requires site-wide quality lift</li>
              <li>Recovery waits for the next Core Update</li>
              <li>Google's guidance: no specific fix, improve overall quality</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Targeted update signals</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Ranking shifts limited to a specific issue</li>
              <li>Named target: spam, links, reviews, content</li>
              <li>Fix maps directly to the target</li>
              <li>Recovery when the targeted system re-runs</li>
              <li>Google's guidance usually names the specific problem</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for surviving algorithm updates</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Track updates in a shared log.</strong> Maintain a spreadsheet with every named update, its date, and your traffic delta. Pattern-matching future updates gets faster.</li>
          <li><strong>Do not react during rollout.</strong> Rankings bounce for the first 5 to 7 days. Any panic edits inside that window pollute your diagnosis.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch your worst-performing content.</strong> The bottom 20% of your pages usually drag your quality score. Prune, rewrite, or noindex them.</li>
          <li><strong>Build for durability, not the current signal.</strong> Every update chases quality signals humans already value — depth, experience, and expertise are always safe bets.</li>
          <li><strong>Diversify beyond Google.</strong> AI answer engines, LinkedIn organic, newsletter distribution — every channel offsets algorithm-update risk.</li>
          <li><strong>Read the Search Liaison's posts.</strong> Danny Sullivan tells you what the update targets in plain English.</li>
          <li><strong>Compare against competitors post-rollout.</strong> If they gained where you lost, the delta is the exact quality gap you have to close.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">The panic-fix trap</div>
          <p>During and immediately after an update, teams delete content, remove backlinks, and change titles based on gut feeling. Almost every one of those edits undermines the actual diagnosis. <strong>Wait for the rollout to finish</strong>, gather full data, then act.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common algorithm update mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Reacting mid-rollout.</strong> Rankings are not stable until Google announces completion.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming every drop is an update.</strong> Seasonality, indexing bugs, and competitor moves all mimic update losses.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing the last update's fix.</strong> The next update tests different signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the winners.</strong> Sites that gained show you what the algorithm now favours.</li>
          <li><strong>Building only for Google.</strong> Diversify traffic sources to survive future updates.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often does Google update its algorithm?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google runs thousands of small ranking changes per year — 4,725 in 2022 by its own reporting. Around 4 to 6 of those are named, confirmed updates like Core Updates, Spam Updates, or Product Reviews Updates. The rest are silent tweaks.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long does a rollout take?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Core Updates typically roll out over 1 to 3 weeks. Spam Updates and Link Spam Updates roll out in days. The full impact on rankings is usually visible 5 to 7 days after Google announces completion.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I know if an update affected my site?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Overlay your Google Search Console traffic against known update dates (Search Engine Land, Semrush Sensor, MozCast). A sharp change in impressions or clicks starting on an update day, with no other explanation, is a strong signal.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What should I do during an update?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Wait for the rollout to finish before reacting — mid-rollout rankings jump around. Once complete, diagnose whether you gained, lost, or held steady, then decide whether a content or link intervention is needed.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can algorithm updates be reversed?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Google does not roll back completed updates. Losses recover only when the site improves enough for the next re-evaluation to score it higher.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

